   <text>
      <body>
         
            
               <p>
                        <persName>Furly (or Furley</persName>) was admitted a pensioner at Queens'
                  College, <placeName>Cambridge</placeName> on <date when="1753-11-02">Nov. 2,
                     1753</date>, and became friendly with <persName>
                            <ptr target="/persons/pers2093.xml"/>Henry Venn</persName>, who was a fellow
                  there. He was ordained as deacon in <date when="1758-05">May 1758</date>, and
                  married <persName>
                            <ptr target="/persons/pers0761.xml"/>Ann Bloodworth</persName>
                  the <date when="1758-06">following month</date>. After brief curacies in
                     <placeName>London</placeName>, <placeName>Lakenheath (Suffolk</placeName>), and
                     <placeName>Kippax (Yorkshire</placeName>), he served as curate of
                     <placeName>Slaithwaite (Yorkshire</placeName>) from <date from="1761" to="1766">1761–66</date>. Then <persName>John Thornton</persName> presented him to the
                  living of <placeName>Roche, Cornwall</placeName>, where he remained rector until
                  his death. <persName>
                            <ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
                  corresponded with him for several years, hoping to bring him into the Methodist
                  network. See <hi rend="italic">Alumni Catabrigienses</hi>; CCEd; and <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 416.</p>
            
         
